AU Optronics, Ayala, LG Display, Poly Glass: Asia Ex-Japan Equity Preview

-- B y   B e r n i   M o e s t a f a
-- 
2011-04-18T21:00:44Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-18/au-optronics-ayala-lg-display-poly-glass-asia-ex-japan-equity-preview.html
The following companies may have
unusual price changes today in Asia trading, excluding  Japan .
Stock symbols are in parentheses, and share prices are from the
previous close, unless noted otherwise.  Ayala Land Inc. (ALI)  : The largest Philippine developer
said profit may reach 10 billion pesos ($231 million) by 2014, a
stock exchange filing showed. The stock fell 0.1 percent to
16.96 pesos.  LG Display Co. (034220 KS): The world’s second-largest
maker of liquid-crystal displays reported a second consecutive
loss after panel prices declined. LG Display had a net loss of
115.4 billion won ($106 million) in the first quarter, according
to a statement from the Seoul-based company. That compares with
the average estimate from 12 analysts surveyed by Bloomberg for
a net loss of 208.4 billion won. LG Display dropped 0.6 percent
to 36,100 won.  Minmetals Resources Ltd. (1208)  (1208 HK): The producer and
distributor of aluminum and copper products plans to sell as
many as 1.2 billion shares at HK$5.20 to HK$5.60 each, according
to a term sheet for the transaction obtained by Bloomberg News.
Minmetals dropped 5.5 percent to HK$5.89 before trading in the
stock was suspended yesterday.  OCI Co. (010060 KS): The South Korean company won a $361
million (392.7 billion won) order to supply polysilicon to  AU
Optronics Corp. (2409)  (2409 TT) of Taiwan by the end of 2018,
according to a regulatory filing from the Korean company. OCI,
which markets inorganic chemicals, petro and coal chemicals,
gained 0.6 percent to 536,000 won. AU Optronics,  Taiwan ’s
second-largest maker of liquid-crystal displays, declined 1.8
percent to NT$24.6.  Poly Glass Fibre (M) Bhd. (PGF MK): The Malaysian
manufacturer of fiber glass wool said it agreed to sell a
warehouse and office building to PM Steel and Alloys Industries
Sdn. for 13 million ringgit ($4.3 million), according to a
company statement. The shares were unchanged at 36.5 sen on
April 14.  Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing Co. (2330 TT): The
world’s largest contract chipmaker bought NT$1.06 billion of
equipment and facilities from two vendors, TSMC said in
statements to the stock exchange. The company purchased NT$520
million of gear from Kanken Techno Co. and NT$535 million of
facilities and engineering equipment from Muratec Automation
Taiwan Ltd., the Hsinchu, Taiwan-based company said. TMSC slid
0.3 percent to NT$69.  -With assistance from Ian C. Sayson in  Manila , Chan Tien Hin in
 Kuala Lumpur . Editor:  To contact the reporter on this story:
